liott%20Cemetery%20in%20Detroit%2C%20Michigan.&f=false |date=2006|publisher= Arcadia Publishing |quote= |ISBN=0738540935}}\n\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last= Loomis|first= Bill|title= Detroit's Detectable Past | url= https://books.google.com/books?id=CYx2CQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Bill+Loomis+2012&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjbhPGEsqboAhWCGs0KHW13Ca4Q6AEwAXoECAQQAg#v=onepage&q=Dwyer&f=false |date=2012|publisher= Arcadia Publishing |quote= |ISBN=1614236275}}\n\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last= Marquis|first= Albert|title= The Book of Detroiters | url= |date=1908|publisher= Albert Nelson Marquis |quote= }}\n\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last= Moore |first= Charles |title= History of Michigan | url= |date=1915|publisher= Lewis Publishing Company |quote= }}\n\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last= Stern|first= Daniel|title= The American Artisan and Hardware Record: Volume 79, No. 1 | url= |date=1920a|publisher= Daniel Stern |quote= }}\n\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last= Taylor|first= Henry|title= Compendium of History of City of Detroit | url= |date=1909|publisher= Henry Taylor & Company |quote= }}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dwyer, Jeremiah}}\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Detroit]]\n[[Category:1837 births]]\n[[Category:1920 deaths]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Michigan Democrats]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American businessman, industrialist, and manufacturer 1837\u20131920}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Jeremiah Dwyer\n| image         = File:Jeremiah Dwyer.jpg\n| caption       = 1903\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|mf=yes|1838|8|22}}\n| birth_place   = [[Brooklyn, New York]], US\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|mf=yes|1920|1|29|1837|8|22}}\n| death_place   = [[Detroit, Michigan]], US\n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality   = American\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = businessman, industrialist, founder & director of firms\n| title         = \n| salary        = \n| networth      = \n| height        = \n| weight        = \n| term          = \n| predecessor   = \n| successor     = \n| party         = \n| boards        = \n| religion      = \n| spouse        = Mary L. Long\n| partner       = \n| children      = 8\n| relatives     = \n| signature     = File:Jeremiah Dwyer signature.jpg\n| website       = \n| footnotes     = }}\n\n'''Jeremiah Dwyer''' (August 22, 1837{{spaced ndash}}January 29, 1920) was an American businessman, industrialist, and manufacturer in [[Detroit, Michigan]]. He had been associated with stove manufacturing for over five decades. Dwyer ran the world's largest producer of stoves at the time, [[Michigan Stove Company]], and was director of several other stove companies. He was then known as \"The Stove King\" because of his association with these firms. He was also on the board of directors with several other businesses in the Detroit area.\n\n== Early life ==\nDwyer was born in the borough of [[Brooklyn]] in New York City on August 22, 1837.{{sfn|Bersey|1890|page=248}}{{sfn|Biographical|1900|page=462}}{{sfn|Farmer|1890|page=1187}} He was the eldest child of Michael Dwyer and Mary (O'Donnell) Dwyer. He had a brother, James, and sister, Mary. His father was born in 1800 and immigrated from Ireland to the United States when he was eighteen years old. He settled initially near [[Hartford, Connecticut]].{{sfn|Founding|1920|page=163}} He moved from Connecticut to Brooklyn two years later in 1820. There he was a contractor's superintendent for many years.{{sfn|Bersey|1890|page=248}} Sometime in the mid 1830s he met and married a young lady by the name of Mary O'Donell that was from his home town in Ireland. Their first child Jeremiah was born in Brooklyn. They moved to Detroit in October 1838 and established a farm in [[Springwells Township, Michigan|Springwells township]] (originally ''Belle-Fontaine'') about four miles from Detroit.{{sfn|Catlin|1898|page=697}}\n\nDwyer learned [[French language|French]] as a young boy in addition to English since most neighbors in Springwells spoke French. Dwyer's parents worked a farm there and this was where his siblings James and Mary were born.{{sfn|Taylor|1909|page=416}}<ref name=James_obit>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= James Dwyer is dead at 69 yrs |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40843359/ |work= Detroit Free Press, vol. 76 - No. 357 |location=Detroit, Michigan |date=September 18, 1911 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref> In 1848 Dwyer's father was killed by being thrown from a runaway wagon, since the horses pulling the wagon were frightened by the noise of a nearby train locomotive and ran out of control.{{sfn|Farmer|1890|page=1188}} Dwyer then assisted his mother in managing the family farm for two years.{{sfn|Catlin|1898|page=697}}<ref name=achievement>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Detroit Men of Achievement |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41362007/ |work= Detroit Free Press |location=Detroit, Michigan |date=November 8, 1903 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref> In 1850 his mother sold the country farm and bought a home in the city of Detroit for the family.{{sfn|Moore|1915|page=682}}\n\n== Mid life ==\nDwyer and his siblings were home schooled for a while. In his teens Dwyer worked part-time for the planing mill of Smith & Dwight and attended Detroit public schools.{{sfn|Stern|1920a|page=31}} After graduating from high school he worked as an apprentice for four years in the moulding trade at hydraulic iron works of Kellogg & Van Schoick.{{sfn|Founding|1920|page=163}}<ref name=apprenticed>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= JEREMIAH DWYER - Pioneer in one of Detroit's greatest industries |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40814194/ |work= Detroit Free Press, part 4 |location=Akron, Ohio |date=September 2, 1906 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref>{{sfn|Burton|1922|page=546}} Dwyer became a journeyman after completing his apprenticeship and worked for three years at various foundries in the state of New York learning the stove business.<ref name=apprenticed/>{{sfn|Taylor|1909|page=417}} He then returned to Detroit and due to health issues as a result of intense work in poorly ventilated foundries it behooved him to change fields for a while.{{sfn|Biographical|1900|page=462}} Dwyer then took employment at the Detroit Grand Haven and Milwaukee railway company for about a year.{{sfn|Taylor|1909|page=417}}{{sfn|Derby|1894|page=300}}\n\nDwyer in 1859 became foreman at the Geary & Russell foundry in Detroit until 1861. Then with his brother James and Thomas W Misner they bought out a small [[reaper]] manufacturer trying to make stoves and was failing.{{sfn|Loomis|2012|page=99}} The three of them made the defunct manufacturer into \"J. Dwyer and Company\" that years later became the joint stock company Detroit Stove Works.{{sfn|Stern|1920a|page=31}}{{sfn|Burton|1922|page=546}} The stock holders were Dwyer and his brother James, W. H. Tefft, and M. I. Mills.{{sfn|Biographical|1900|page=462}} In 1871 Dwyer then organized a new firm under the name of Michigan Stove Company.{{sfn|Stern|1920a|page=31}}{{sfn|Taylor|1909|page=417}}<ref name=InvestorDuCharme>{{cite web |url= https://detroithistorical.org/learn/encyclopedia-of-detroit/detroit-stove-works|title=Encyclopedia Of Detroit - Detroit Stove Works|publisher= Detroit Historical Society |accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref> The stock holders of this company were Dwyer, Mills, R. H. Long, George H. Barbour, and Charles DuCharme.{{sfn|Biographical|1900|page=462}} The company became the largest manufacturers of stoves in the world.<ref name=LargestInWorld>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= The Truth About Stoves |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41394131/ |work= Detroit Free Press |location=Detroit, Michigan |date=October 20, 1905 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref>\n\n== Personal ==\nDwyer married Mary L. Long on November 22, 1859.{{sfn|Biographical|1900|page=462}} They had eight children, seven sons and one daughter. Their names were James W., John M., Elizabeth B., William A., Francis T., Vincent R., Gratton L., and Emmet.{{sfn|Taylor|1909|page=418}} Dwyer liked traveling to Europe on vacations. In Detroit his office address was at 1022 Jefferson Avenue and his residence was at 692 Jefferson Avenue.{{sfn|Hamersly|1909|page=539}} He held a membership in the Detroit Country Club.{{sfn|Marquis|1908|page=155}} Dwyer associated with the Democrat party and was a Catholic.{{sfn|Taylor|1909|page=418}}\n[[File:World's Largest Stove.jpg|thumb|upright 0.8|World's Largest Stove]]\n\n== Businesses and associations ==\nDwyer served as a member on the Board of Estimates for two terms. He was Trustee of the Fire Department Society.{{sfn|Biographical|1900|page=462}} Dwyer for twenty-four years was commissioner and inspector of the Detroit [[Detroit Detention Center| House of Corrections]].{{sfn|Stern|1920a|page=31}} Dwyer was one of the founders the People's Savings Bank and a director at the Peoples State Bank of Detroit. He was board member at Michigan Stove, Peninsular Stove, Art Stove, Buck's Stove, Michigan Copper & Brass, Michigan Fire and Marine Insurance, Security Trust, and Ideal Manufacturing of Detroit.{{sfn|Stern|1920a|page=31}} Dwyer was known as \"The Stove King\" when operating the stove companies.{{sfn|Collins|1914|page=4}}\n\nDwyer received from [[George Harrison Barbour]], the vice president of Michigan Stove Company, the idea of constructing the [[World's Largest Stove]] for the 1893 Chicago World's Fair and had his plant superintendent [[William J. Keep]] design the mammoth Garland kitchen range that weighed 15 tons.<ref name=HotStoves>{{cite web |url= https://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/local/michigan-history/2015/01/24/stove-capital-detroit-history/22234051/ |title=When stoves were the hot new thing|publisher= The Detroit News|accessdate=January 7, 2020|quote= To grab attention at the Chicago World's Columbian Exposition of 1893, George H. Barbour, vice president of the Michigan Stove Co., had his woodcarvers replicate on a gigantic scale a Garland brand model kitchen range built by the firm. Factory superintendent William J. Keep designed the huge stove and had it carved in oak. It measured 25 feet high, 30 feet long, and 20 feet wide. Painted to look like metal, it stood at the Chicago exposition on a platform 20 feet high over an exhibit of regular stoves. The Michigan Stove Co. built a gigantic, 25 feet high, 15 ton wooden replica of a Garland kitchen range, painted to look like metal, for the Chicago World\u2019s Columbian Exposition of 1893. }}</ref><ref name=SeekMich>{{cite web |url= https://seekingmichigan.org/look/2009/06/09/now-were-cooking |title=Seeking Michigan|publisher= Seeking Michigan|accessdate=January 7, 2020|quote= George H. Barbour, vice-president of the Michigan Stove Company, conceived the idea for this giant replica stove. He used it to promote the company\u2019s \u201cGarland\u201d model at the 1893 Columbian Exposition in Chicago. William J. Keep designed the replica, sculpted from oak by John Tabaczuk and Joachim Jungwirth. The massive oaken replica stove was painted to appear metal, weighed fifteen tons, measured twenty-five feet high, thirty feet long and twenty feet wide. }}</ref><ref name=crier>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= The Town Crier |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41604609/|newspaper= Detroit Free Press |page=60  |location=Howell, Michigan|date= February 18, 1965|quote=\nFact supplied by the Detroit Historical Commission credits George Barbour, then vice president of Michigan Stove,with the idea for the stove to be built and displayed at the Exposition to dramatize Detroit's position as \"stove capital of the country.\" It was designed by the superintendent of Michigan Stove, William Keep. Constructed of oak, it stands 25 feet high, is 30 feet long 20 feet high, weighs 15 tons.   |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref>\n\n== Later life and death ==\nDwyer suffered various illnesses for years toward the end of his life that caused him to withdraw from his business affairs. He died at the age of 82 on January 29, 1920. At the time of his death he had four sons and one daughter still living. They were John M Dwyer, William A Dwyer, Emmett Dwyer, Grattan L Dwyer; and Mrs Elizabeth B. Smith of Cleveland. His wife had died in 1919.{{sfn|Stern|1920a|page=31}} He is buried in [[Eastside Historic Cemetery District|Mount Elliott Cemetery]] in Detroit, Michigan.{{sfn|Jensen|2006|page=29}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Commons category|Michigan Stove Company}}\n\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last= Bersey|first= John|title= Cyclopedia of Michigan | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5kcAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA4-PA248&dq=JEREMIAH+DWYER+was+born+New+York+August+22+1837&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiamJfhsd7mAhXaB50JHVOkCYcQ6AEwAXoECAUQAg#v=onepage&q=JEREMIAH%20DWYER%20was%20born%20New%20York%20August%2022%201837&f=false |date=1890|publisher= Western Publishing & Engraving |quote= }}\n\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last= Biographical|first= Press|title= The Successful American, V.3 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cGpMAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA462&dq=%22Jeremiah+Dwyer%22++biography&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj_xKWRqN7mAhWRHc0KHSXgAN4Q6AEwA3oECAcQAg#v=onepage&q=%22Jeremiah%20Dwyer%22%20%20biography&f=false |date=1900|publisher= Press Biographical Company |quote= }}\n\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last= Burton|first=Clarence |title= City of Detroit, V.1 | url=  |date=1922|publisher= S. J. Clarke Publishing Company |quote= }}\n\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last= Catlin |first= George|title= Landmarks of Detroit | url= |date=1898|publisher= The Evening News Association |quote= }}\n\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last= Collins|first= S