on\n| title              = 2020 LCS season\n| league             = [[League of Legends Championship Series|LCS]]\n| sport              = ''[[League of Legends]]''\n| duration           = {{nowrap|January 25 \u2013 April 19 (Spring)<br />June 20 \u2013 September 13 (Summer)}}\n| no_of_matches      =\n| no_of_teams        = 10\n| TV                 = '''English:''' [[ESPN2]], [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]], [[YouTube]]<br />'''Chinese:''' [[Huya Live|Huya]]\n| season             = Spring\n| top_seed           = [[Cloud9]]\n| MVP                = Robert \"Blaber\" Huang<ref>{{cite news |last1=Stavropoulos |first1=Andreas |title=C9 Blaber wins 2020 LCS Spring MVP award |url=https://dotesports.com/league-of-legends/news/c9-blaber-wins-2020-lcs-spring-mvp-award |accessdate=April 18, 2020 |work=Dot Esports |date=April 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ousley |first1=Parkes |title=League of Legends: Cloud9 Blaber is your 2020 LCS Spring Split Honda MVP |url=https://www.invenglobal.com/articles/11001/cloud9-blaber-is-your-2020-lcs-spring-split-honda-mvp |accessdate=April 18, 2020 |work=InvenGlobal |date=April 17, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n| MVP_link           =\n| season_champ_name  =\n| season_champs      =\n| second_place       =\n<!-- Uncomment when results are final\n| season2            = Summer\n| top_seed2          =\n| MVP2               =\n| MVP_link2          =\n| season_champ2_name =\n| season_champs2     =\n| second_place2      =\n-->\n| seasonslist        =\n| seasonslistnames   = LCS\n| prevseason_link    = 2019 LCS season\n| prevseason_year    = 2019\n| nextseason_link    = 2021 LCS season\n| nextseason_year    = ''2021''\n}}\n\nThe '''2020 LCS season''' is the third year [[Sports franchise|under partnership]] and eighth overall of the [[League of Legends Championship Series|''League of Legends'' Championship Series]] (LCS), a professional [[esports]] league for the [[Multiplayer online battle arena|MOBA]] [[PC game]] ''[[League of Legends]]''. It is the first year that the league will use a [[Double-elimination tournament|double elimination bracket]] for its [[playoff format]]. Championship points and the regional finals were also removed from the [[League of Legends World Championship|World Championship]] qualification process.<ref name=\"Dot1\">{{cite news |last1=Esguerra |first1=Tyler |title=Riot changes LCS playoff format for 2020, will also remove NA regional qualifiers |url=https://dotesports.com/league-of-legends/news/riot-changes-lcs-playoff-format-for-2020-will-also-remove-na-regional-qualifiers |accessdate=January 18, 2020 |work=Dot Esports |date=January 8, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"TheGamer1\">{{cite news |last1=Rutledge |first1=Caroline |title=Riot Games Announces Major LCS Format Changes Ahead of 2020 Season |url=https://www.thegamer.com/riot-games-announces-lcs-format-changes-2020-season/ |accessdate=January 18, 2020 |work=TheGamer |date=January 8, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"GGIntel1\">{{cite news |last1=Stewart |first1=Jack |title=LCS introduces double elimination Playoffs and stronger Academy investment for 2020 |url=https://www.ggintel.com/articles/lcs-introduces-double-elimination-playoffs-and-stronger-academy-investment-for-2020 |accessdate=January 18, 2020 |work=GGIntel |date=January 8, 2020 |language=EN}}</ref><ref name=\"VP1\">{{cite news |last1=Kolev |first1=Radoslav |title=LCS restructures Worlds qualification method, finally introduces double elimination bracket |url=https://www.vpesports.com/leagueoflegends/lcs-restructures-worlds-qualification-method-finally-introduces-double-elimination-bracket/ |accessdate=January 18, 2020 |work=VPEsports |date=January 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe spring split began on January 25 and was scheduled to conclude with the spring finals on April 19; however, due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|spread of COVID-19 in the United States]], the season was temporarily suspended on March 13.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Esguerra |first1=Tyler |title=Riot suspends LCS season, moves 2020 Spring Finals to Los Angeles |url=https://dotesports.com/league-of-legends/news/riot-suspends-lcs-season-moves-2020-spring-finals-to-los-angeles |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |work=Dot Esports |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Four days later, it was announced that the LCS would resume on March 20, with all matches being played online.\n\nThe summer split will begin on June 20 and conclude with the summer finals on September 13.<ref name=\"TheGamer1\"/><ref name=\"GGIntel1\"/>\n\n== League changes ==\n[[Riot Games]] announced several changes to the LCS on January 8.<ref name=\"Dot1\"/><ref name=\"TheGamer1\"/><ref name=\"GGIntel1\"/><ref name=\"VP1\"/>\n\n=== Playoff format ===\nFrom the 2020 season onwards, the LCS will use a double elimination bracket as its playoff format,<ref name=\"Dot1\"/><ref name=\"GGIntel1\"/><ref name=\"VP1\"/> similar to that which was adopted by the [[League of Legends European Championship|LEC]] the previous year.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Esguerra |first1=Lawrence Tyler |title=LEC introduces a new season format for 2019 |url=https://www.dailyesports.gg/lec-introduces-new-season-format/ |accessdate=January 21, 2020 |work=Daily Esports |date=January 15, 2019}}</ref> The number of teams participating in the spring playoffs will remain unchanged at six, but the summer playoffs will include an additional two teams, bringing the total up to eight. Both splits will feature a winners' bracket and a losers' bracket, with the bottom two teams beginning in the losers' and the rest beginning in the winners'.<ref name=\"TheGamer1\"/><ref name=\"VP1\"/>\n\n=== Schedule ===\nThe LCS schedule was revised for the 2020 season. Four LCS games will broadcast each Saturday and Sunday instead of five, and two games will air during \"Monday Night League\", which will feature the two most popular matchups of the week.<ref name=\"TheGamer1\"/><ref name=\"GGIntel1\"/><ref name=\"VP1\"/> LCS commissioner Chris Greeley explained that this was done to give less popular teams and players more exposure and opportunities to develop their brand, as most viewers, he argued, only tune in to watch their favorite teams.<ref name=\"VP1\"/>\n\n=== International qualifications ===\nChampionship points and the regional finals were removed from the LCS prior to the start of the 2020 season.<ref name=\"TheGamer1\"/><ref name=\"GGIntel1\"/> The results of the spring split will only determine the LCS' representative for the [[Mid-Season Invitational]], and will no longer have any part in determining a team's future qualification for the World Championship. The summer champions, runners-up and third place team will qualify for the World Championship as the LCS' first, second and third seeds respectively.<ref name=\"VP1\"/>\n\n== Broadcasting ==\nThe English broadcast is available on the LoL Esports website, as well as on [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Brathwaite |first1=Brandon |title=Riot Games Pilots Twitch Co-Streaming for NA LCS |url=https://esportsobserver.com/riot-games-co-streaming/ |accessdate=January 20, 2020 |work=The Esports Observer |date=September 14, 2018}}</ref> and [[YouTube]].<ref name=\"Matthiesen\">{{cite news |last1=Matthiesen |first1=Tom |title=League of Legends: Riot partners with Huya as exclusive platform to broadcast the LCS and LEC in China |url=https://www.invenglobal.com/articles/10211/riot-partners-with-huya-as-exclusive-platform-to-broadcast-the-lcs-and-lec-in-china |accessdate=January 20, 2020 |work=Inven Global |date=January 20, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> On January 20, Riot Games announced their official partnership with Chinese streaming service [[Huya Live|Huya]], giving them exclusive rights to the Chinese broadcast.<ref name=\"Matthiesen\"/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Esguerra |first1=Tyler |title=Huya becomes newest exclusive LCS and LEC broadcaster in China |url=https://dotesports.com/league-of-legends/news/huya-becomes-newest-exclusive-lcs-and-lec-broadcaster-in-china |accessdate=January 20, 2020 |work=Dot Esports |date=January 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Murray |first1=Trent |title=Huya Secures Chinese Broadcast Rights for LCS, LEC |url=https://esportsobserver.com/lcslec-china-huya/ |accessdate=January 20, 2020 |work=The Esports Observer |date=January 20, 2020}}</ref> On April 8, it was announced that the spring playoffs would be aired on [[ESPN2]] and the ESPN App.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ocal |first1=Arda |title=LCS spring split playoff games to air on ESPN |url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/29012471/lcs-spring-split-playoff-games-air-espn |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=ESPN |date=April 8, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Spring ==\n\n=== Teams and rosters ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Team\n! colspan=\"5\" | Roster\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Coach\n|-\n! Top\n! Jungle\n! Mid\n! Bot\n! Support\n|-\n| '''[[100 Thieves]]'''\n| {{flagicon|KOR}} Ssumday\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Meteos (video game player)|Meteos]]\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} Ryoma\n| {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Cody Sun]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} Stunt\n| {{flagicon|USA}} Zikz\n|-\n| '''[[Cloud9]]'''\n| {{flagicon|CAN}} Licorice\n| {{flagicon|USA}} Blaber\n| {{flagicon|BEL}} Nisqy\n| {{flagicon|DEN}} Zven\n| {{flagicon|CAN}} Vulcan\n| {{flagicon|KOR}} Reapered\n|-\n| '''[[Counter Logic Gaming]]'''\n| {{flagicon|KOR}} Ruin\n| {{flagicon|USA}} Wiggily\n| {{flagicon|KOR}} Crown<br />{{flagicon|USA}} [[Pobelter]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Stixxay]]<br />{{flagicon|KOR}} Wind\n| {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Smoothie (video game player)|Smoothie]]\n| {{flagicon|KOR}} SSONG\n|-\n| '''[[Dignitas (esports)|Dignitas]]'''\n| {{flagicon|KOR}} [[Huni (video game player)|Huni]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} Akaadian<br />{{flagicon|USA}} Grig\n| {{flagicon|DEN}} [[Froggen]]\n| {{flagicon|CAN}} Johnsun \n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[aphromoo]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} Thinkcard\n|-\n| '''[[Evil Geniuses]]'''\n| {{flagicon|USA}} Kumo\n| {{flagicon|DEN}} [[Svenskeren]]\n| {{fla